An entrepreneur with a registered office, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic whose turnover exceeds CZK 1,000,000 in the last 12 consecutive calendar months shall be liable for payment on the first day of the third month after the month in which he has exceeded the threshold (§ 94 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004 Coll., concerning VAT; hereinafter "Law No. 235 / 2004").
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he has exceeded the registration threshold.
Current legislation does not allow the retroactive registration of a tax payer if it has exceeded the registration deadline.
An entrepreneur with a legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic who provides sales tax services or services exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT must register for VAT even if his turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million but fulfils other conditions set out in Law No 235 / 2004.
An entrepreneur with a legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic who does not meet any of the conditions set out in the law may voluntarily apply for registration for VAT.
The registration procedure in accordance with Law No 337 / 1992 begins when the application for registration is received by the local tax official.
If you want to register voluntarily for sales tax, you must specify in your application the cut-off date from which you apply for registration as a sales tax payer.
The financial officer must examine the information provided by the trader, i.e. the completed application for registration with all the installations.
If he has doubts about the information contained therein, he must ask the applicant to explain, supplement or prove the information provided.
If the financial officer has verified that the entrepreneur fulfils the conditions for registration, he has to give a written notification of the registration and the allocation of a tax number.
In the communication, the financial officer must indicate the date of entry into force of the registration of the sales tax and the assessment period for the sales tax.
The investment period is the calendar quarter, unless the entrepreneur's turnover for the previous calendar year has reached the amount of at least CZK 10,000,000.
If this is the case, the predisposition period is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur whose turnover in the previous calendar year has reached at least CZK 2,000,000 is entitled to choose the calendar month as an investment period and must inform the financial officer of this change.
The granting of a tax number in the registration order is always constitutive.
The tax-payer must provide the tax number for each communication (including payments) with the tax official, as well as in cases where this is required by a special law (e.g. Law No 235 / 2004, concerning the production of tax documents) 3.
The control number contains the coding "CZ" and a basic component in the form of a general identification sign.
In the case of natural persons, this is the number of the birth certificate or another general identification sign, insofar as this is determined by a special law.
If, despite a request from the finance official, the entrepreneur has not fulfilled his lease, the local finance official must register him on his own initiative.
A decision will also be made on this, which will go to the tax payer.
In the Czech Republic, each trader admitted to a business activity will receive a tax number for any type of tax at the time of his first registration.
This also applies to registration as a VAT payer.
In accordance with Law No 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, in the event of non-fulfilment of the obligation to register the turnover tax, the tax officer may require that up to 10% of the proceeds from the tax-related turnover that the person concerned has unlawfully made without taxation, for the period from the date from which the trader should have been registered as a tax agent, until the date on which the registration as a tax officer was made by the order of the tax officer (§ 98 (1) of Law No 235 / 2004).
The payment of the amount set in this way is considered to be a tax payment within the meaning of § 98 (3) of Law No 235 / 2004, i.e. it is not a fine or a penalty.
If the legal requirements are met, the registration of a VAT holder can be deleted for two reasons:
1)
Deletion of registration at the request of the tax office, i.e. mainly because the turnover does not reach the threshold for registration (§ 106 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004).
A tax payer may request the deletion of his registration at the earliest one year after the date of entry into force specified in the registration notice.
2) Deletion of the registration on its own initiative (§ 106 (7) of Law No 235 / 2004) if: a) the tax payer has not provided a service for the period of 12 consecutive months and has not informed the tax official of the reasons for this, b) the tax payer has not fulfilled its obligations under Law No 235 / 2004, c) the previous tax payer no longer fulfils the requirements for the tax levies.
B) Taxpayers without legal domicile, registered office or business premises in the Czech Republic A person who is registered for tax purposes in another Member State and does not have his legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, or a taxable foreigner who provides services in the Czech Republic and has to file a tax return and pay taxes for such services or deliveries in accordance with § 108 of Law No 235 / 2004 ("non-resident entrepreneur") shall be taxed with the provision of the service in question.
He must submit an application for registration with FA Prague 1 at the latest on the day of the delivery in question.
He is required to indicate in this application all the VAT ID numbers assigned to him in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than on the day of the first taxable provision of services in the Czech Republic, the FA Prague 1 has to register him retroactively, as he became taxable in accordance with Law No 235 / 2004 on the day of the first taxable provision of services in the Czech Republic.
In the event of retroactive registration, FA Prague 1 shall require the contractors concerned to provide proof (invoices or written explanations) of the performance.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration in the Czech Republic before performing a service for the first time, the FA Prague 1 must demand the submission of the contract documents on the basis of performance.
As of 31 December 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with FA Prague 1, 124 of them from Germany. As of 31 December 2005, 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered, 233 of them from Germany.
In accordance with the provisions of § 106 (9) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the financial officer is entitled to cancel the registration of a non-resident entrepreneur as of 31 January of the following calendar year, if he does not accept the obligation to submit tax declarations or declarations and to pay taxes.
The examination of the NKÚ showed that in the case of the submission of a tax return by post with dispatch abroad on 25 January, i.e. in accordance with the obligatory deadline for the submission of a tax return, this declaration had not yet been received by the FA by 31 January.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant to the possibility of deletion of registration, become known to the FA later than 31 January, it is no longer possible to delete the registration of the non-resident entrepreneur for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year in question.
Registration of tax payers in Germany
In accordance with the provisions of the tax regulation (§ 137, 138 AO), each business operation must be registered with the municipality and / or the competent tax office.
This registration must be made no later than one month after the commencement of business activities.
The municipality passes on the registration to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office finds that a business activity has been started but has not been notified, it can also register the tax payers retroactively on its own initiative.
In Germany, tax payers, irrespective of whether they are resident or not resident, are leased for registration for purposes of sales tax if they meet the requirements of § 2 of the German VAT Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the amount of turnover achieved.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Entrepreneurs resident abroad are responsible for special FÄ.
For example, for those entrepreneurs based in the Czech Republic, the FA ChemnitzSüd is responsible.
As of 30 April 2004, 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered; as of 1 March 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there.
According to the Federal Republic of Germany, these FÄ with special competences frequently refused to register so-called bogus self-employed persons residing in the new Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since the free movement of workers is still restricted after the accession of these ten countries to the European Union, these self-employed people tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These (note) self-employed persons do not meet the conditions laid down in § 2 of the UStG for recognition as an entrepreneur, as they are usually dependent on a single client who determines their working time and the way in which they carry out their work.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must fill in a questionnaire from the competent FA and provide information on the company and the business activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a binding form for all FÄ in Germany.
It is processed either in special organisational units within the FÄ or in the organisational units generally responsible for the tax assessment.
With the help of this form, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual tax payer before the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic transactions is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the competent FA, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, the following five (or four) digits are the identification feature for the tax payer, the last digit is always a control digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he needs a VAT ID in order to be able to make duty-free intra-Community deliveries.
This will be allocated by the CLO on request if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for sales tax purposes.
The VAT ID number is automatically allocated by the CLO if the tax payer declares intra-Community deliveries in its VAT pre-registrations or in its annual VAT declaration.
The USt-IdNr. consists of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (e.g. when he stops doing business), but only after the completion of all tax transactions (predisposition of all financial years) or 2. If the financial administration determines that he no longer runs a business.
As a rule, the validity of the VAT ID number depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In such cases, the FÄ must notify the CLO of the deletion of the VAT number so that the validity of the VAT ID number can be terminated there at that time.
According to the VAT Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic tax payers do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. the turnover of the previous calendar year plus the subsequent sales tax has not exceeded the amount of €17,500 and 2. will probably not exceed the amount of €50,000 in the following year.
The so-called small entrepreneurs are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay sales tax, small entrepreneurs are required to register with the tax office and submit an annual sales tax return.
A small entrepreneur can declare the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the following five years.
He may then invoice the sales tax and deduct the advance tax.
Non-resident tax payers can appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that they only make tax-free transactions and refrain from deducting VAT.
The fiscal representative fulfils the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so that he does not have to register for sales tax purposes.
The bills indicate that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
Whereas in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is the exceeding of the threshold set out in the VAT law.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardised, but differences can occur due to different organisational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the tax payer will receive a tax number for any tax at the time of his first registration.
In the case of its registration for the VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for sales tax purposes receives a tax number exclusively for intra-German transactions.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must specifically apply for the allocation of a VAT ID number.
Both the NKÚ and the BRH found that the German two-tier registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which allocates a single identification number both for national VAT registration and for intra-Community transactions, could lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows for retroactive (national registration) in cases where the tax payer does not register his business with the municipality or the competent FA.
This retroactive registration allows an accurate assessment of the value added tax for previous investment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the value added tax debt.
As the different registration procedures cause problems, the rules for the whole of the EC should be harmonised.
The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Office for Taxes to each natural person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons resident in Germany for life.
If a natural person takes up a business activity, the competent FA applies for a commercial tax identification number, which serves as a VAT ID number.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a tax payer and the allocation of the VAT ID number.
Work on the implementation of an IT procedure for the management of numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach
Legislative provisions in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of § 70 of Law No 235 / 2004, since 1 May 2004, the carriage of passengers between Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and is entitled to a deduction of VAT.
The VAT exemption will also apply if the carriage is carried out by persons registered as tax payers in other Member States or by foreigners who are taxable domestically.
The return journey is considered to be a separate transport process.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than the cross-border transport of passengers by bus and coach, they are not required to register in the Czech Republic as subject to sales tax.
Cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic has been exempted from VAT on the basis of the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b).
"For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77 / 388 / EEC, in accordance with point 17 in Annex F to the Directive, the Czech Republic may maintain the exemption for cross-border passenger transport either until the condition of Article 28 (4) of the Directive is met or as long as the same exemption is applied by any of the current Member States."
The legal regulations in Germany
In accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by § 3b (1) of the UStG, a carriage service is carried out where the carriage is carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is tax-exempt in Germany.
German taxation also does not distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident tax payer transports a person through Germany, the part of the carriage incurred in Germany is considered to be tax-free transport.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must notify his intention to provide passenger transport services to the competent FA.
This registers it for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and gives a special certificate for each bus mentioned in the registration of the tax office.
The entrepreneur must indicate his tax-related transport services in a German VAT return.
As of 1 March 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the FA Chemnitz-Süd.
If the transport service is provided for a resident entrepreneur, the non-resident tax payer does not have to pay the sales tax to the FA himself.
In its place, the domestic customer of the services must pay the VAT to the tax office and the net amount invoiced to the non-resident tax payer, which is referred to as the "transfer of the tax liability" and is in accordance with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident tax payer and his income tax return, the German tax administration has several means to check the correctness of the tax return with regard to tax-related personal promotions:
Mobile customs control groups check the certificates of buses and coaches registered abroad, which are used for passenger transport through Germany.
After each inspection, the mobile control groups transmit an inspection protocol to the competent FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group can ask the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident tax payer can deduct the sales tax paid in this way from the tax debt stated in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts as to the correctness of a VAT return, it may order an examination to be carried out in the FA or may use the means of mutual assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign tax payer refuses to pay the legally fixed turnover tax, the FA may request assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these funds of mutual assistance in tax matters for the verification of the VAT return or compliance with the tax burden by a non-resident bus operator to be too burdensome in relation to the small amount of the turnover tax on tax-bound passenger transport.
In particular, auditing the books of a non-resident tax payer incurs disproportionately high costs for the tax payer himself and for the financial administration.
The latter must examine foreign books, which requires not only knowledge of the foreign language, but also of foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an examination is expected to involve a higher amount of time than a resident tax payer, although the examination is limited to the passenger transports carried out in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident tax payer must accept not only the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States, insofar as he carries out passenger transport there.
In addition, for each Member State in which a single passenger transport is carried out, the tax-payer must comply with all existing tax requirements in the different languages and on the basis of the forms provided by the financial administrations of the EC Member States concerned.
As a result, the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services leads to a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation varies between the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States as well as between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT under the Act of Accession to the EC of the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to sales tax in accordance with the transport route incurred on German territory.
If a non-resident tax payer provides such a transport service for the first time, he must notify it to the relevant FA beforehand.
This registers the tax payer, who has to declare the tax-deductible share of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
Law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax payers registered with the FA Chemnitz-Süd have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The tax revenue in question is quite low in relation to the administrative burden.
Member States - which levy VAT in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of value added tax - have a high administrative burden relative to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionate costs of the VAT predisposition, cross-border passenger transport should only be taxable in one Member State.
This could be the state in which the carriage begins or in which the service provider is established.
Such a form of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
Sales tax returns
Submission and processing of VAT declarations in the Czech Republic
Unless the law stipulates otherwise, even if no tax debt has been incurred, the entrepreneur is required to submit a VAT return on the form set by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the expiry of the tax period.
The tax liability is incurred at the expiry of the period for the submission of the VAT return. Excluded from this provision is the VAT on the import of goods according to Law No. 235 / 2004.
If there is a refund entitlement as a result of above-average deductible advance taxes, this amount will be refunded to the taxable person within 30 days of the deduction being set, without the need to make an application for it.
The deadline will not be applied in cases where the tax official initiates a tax procedure with regard to the tax liability of the tax payer.
Pursuant to § 73 (11) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the right to deduction of VAT may be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the right to deduction of VAT has arisen.
After the expiry of this period, the deduction can still be claimed within three years of the end of the tax period during which it would have been possible to apply for the first time.
However, this requires the submission of a supplementary sales tax return.
An amendment to Law No 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, allows the submission of a supplementary VAT return only for the period during which the right to deduction of VAT could have been asserted for the first time.
A tax payer must make a supplementary VAT return if: a) the sum of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax debt, b) he makes corrections which do not change the last known tax debt, but only change previous information, c) he makes corrections to the VAT rate and the tax debt in accordance with § 49 of Law No. 235 / 2004.
A tax payer can make a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax debt.
The tax payer must submit the supplementary tax return by the end of the month following the month in which the facts in question have been established.
The sales tax return can be submitted electronically either via the Internet or by means of data carriers.
The surrender via the Internet can be done with a certified electronic signature or without it.
If it is done without an electronic signature, it must also be submitted to data carriers.
The form for the VAT return contains separate lines for indicating the value of intra-Community deliveries and acquisitions.
The value of related services must be indicated in separate lines of the VAT return.
Some headings are used for automated primary controls under the ATIS system.
The value of the goods delivered to other EC Member States to persons registered there as tax-exempt is compared with the data provided by the Czech tax authorities in their summary notifications.
The value of the purchases of goods from other Member States from persons registered there as taxable persons is compared with the information in the summary notifications of tax authorities from other EC Member States with the help of MIAS.
Within the framework of the ATIS system, the FA carries out a credibility check of the VAT returns.
This is done automatically, as the VAT return cannot be processed without the prior examination.
The credibility test includes a calculation of the benchmarks for credibility and an assessment of the risks of the VAT returns.
In accordance with the provisions of § 37 (1) of Law No 337 / 1992, the FA may repeatedly impose a fine of up to CZK 2 million on persons who do not comply with their non-monetary obligations under this or a special tax law or a decision under this law.
Automated tax information system - Automated tax information system used by the Czech tax offices to provide technical support for tax collection.
In its investigation, the NKÚ found that the FÄ rarely made use of the possibility of imposing a fine on the tax payer in question if the VAT return was not issued.
Submission and processing of VAT declarations in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly VAT advance notifications and the annual VAT return.
Those tax payers who are leased to submit VAT advance notifications will still have to make an annual VAT return.
Even small entrepreneurs who are not leased to pay the sales tax must make an annual VAT return.
In principle, the tax payers are required to submit a VAT advance notification until the 10th day after the end of the calendar quarter in which the sales tax is incurred (§ 18 (2) UStG).
However, if the VAT debt exceeds €6,136 in the previous year or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is required to submit monthly VAT advance notifications no later than the 10th day after the end of the month in question.
The tax payer can also opt for the submission of monthly VAT advance registrations if he has been reimbursed an amount of more than €6,136 in the previous year (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual turnover tax is no more than €512, no advance VAT notifications or VAT returns are to be made.
A resulting VAT debt must be paid 10 days after the expiry of the tax period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the financial administration.
(Legal) deadlines for the processing of VAT returns and for the refund of VAT overpayments do not exist.
In order to obtain a timely refund, a security for the refund amount can be offered.
In principle, VAT declarations, including reimbursement cases, must be processed quickly.
The German VAT Act allows an extension of these (surrender or payment) deadlines (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the VAT advance notifications and the corresponding payments may be made one month later, but in the case of monthly notifications a special advance payment must be made.
This payment will be offset against the VAT debt established for the pre-registration period of December.
If an error is discovered, the entrepreneur must submit a corrected VAT advance notification.
There is no "supplementary" VAT return.
Once the VAT return to be submitted by 31 May of the following year has been submitted to the tax office, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect VAT advance application, but only the incorrect annual VAT return.
Corrections to this VAT return to the advantage or disadvantage of the tax payer are possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT return was issued.
After the expiry of this four-year period, a VAT return can usually only be corrected in cases of reckless tax reduction or tax evasion.
The tax payers must submit the VAT advance notifications electronically.
The FÄ can grant exemptions to this rule in order to avoid unreasonable hardship.
The annual VAT return can be issued either in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the levy is made without certification, the tax payer must additionally make the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
If no advance VAT declarations or declarations are made, the tax administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover achieved by the tax payer.
In the event of a late levy, the tax payer can be charged a late surcharge (up to 10% of the tax debt or up to an amount of €25,000).
In an earlier audit, the BRH found that the FÄ often do not levy this late surcharge.
In the cases where the FÄ levied the late surcharges, the amount was set inconsistently and arbitrarily.
The late surcharge therefore misses its purpose of reducing the average delay, in particular when submitting the annual VAT return.
The form of the VAT return contains separate lines for value indications for intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions.
There are also separate lines for obtaining services.
Non-taxable transactions must be indicated in a separate line of the VAT return.
The VAT returns submitted on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially designated staff.
The data of electronically submitted tax returns are directly available to the tax administration.
