Although the financial administration only has to make a rough estimate of the VAT debt, it still has to be as accurate as possible.
Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax payers must submit their VAT returns no later than 25 days after the expiry of the tax period.
Depending on the turnover of the tax payer, the tax period is either the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
In Germany, the tax payers must submit their advance applications at the latest 10 days after the end of the calendar quarter or the calendar month, depending on the amount of their tax debt of the previous year.
The annual VAT declaration must be issued by 31 May of the following year at the latest.
The requirement to issue an annual VAT return has some advantages and disadvantages:
+ After the end of the calendar year, the tax payer may correct the errors in the monthly advance notifications by submitting a single VAT return;
- If the tax payer corrects its information on intra-Community transactions, the correction cannot be attributed to a specific reporting period of the ZM;
The federal states do not compare MIAS data on intra-Community acquisitions of German tax payers until the annual VAT declarations have usually been processed.
According to the registration (see 4.1.3), German entrepreneurs must submit a VAT return irrespective of the amount of their turnover.
This levy will enable the German financial administration to verify compliance with the turnover ceiling for small entrepreneurs.
In addition, the competent FA may compare the annual VAT declaration with the corresponding declarations for direct taxes and with the annual financial statements of the company concerned.
In the Czech Republic, the tax administration can only check the amount of the turnover on the basis of the income tax return issued.
In contrast to the current regulations in the Czech Republic, German tax payers are leased to the electronic levy of the VAT advance registration.
The introduction of the requirement for electronic filing of the tax return in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech financial administration.
Summary notifications
Submission and processing of summary notifications in the Czech Republic
Pursuant to the provisions of § 102 of Law No 235 / 2004, an entrepreneur supplying goods to a person registered for tax purposes in another Member State must submit corresponding summary notifications (hereinafter referred to as "ZM").
The value of the goods delivered is always indicated in the ZM in Czech currency, broken down according to the USt-IdNr7, the individual tax authorities under which they are registered in the other Member State.
Information on services is not provided in the ZM.
The tax payers with a calendar monthly or quarterly tax period must surrender the ZM to the local FA at the latest on the 25th day after the end of each quarter.
Incorrect data must be corrected in a corrective ZM within 15 days of the detection of the error.
Erroneous data in the ZM will always be replaced by the data from the correction ZM.
Similar to the tax returns, the tax payers can also hand over the ZM electronically.
In the event of non-compliance with non-monetary obligations, the financial officer shall be entitled to impose repeated fines of up to CZK 2 million in accordance with § 37 of Law No 337 / 1992.
In its investigation, the NKÚ found that the FÄ usually did not use their power to impose fines on their defaulting tax payers.
In particular, in the case of the levy of the ZM, the tax payers are not sufficiently motivated to fulfil their obligations, as the failure to levy a ZM does not affect the amount of their VAT debt.
In accordance with § 102 (5) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the financial officer is required to check the information in the ZM or Amending ZM, to remove all ambiguities and to use the information to determine the tax liability.
