The financial officer must correct the data on deliveries of goods to other Member States in the ATIS system if:
- the tax authority does not prove the correctness of the information reported in the ZM (or Amending ZM) and therefore corrects it by submitting an Amending ZM;
- the financial officer has demonstrated the incorrectness of the information reported by the tax officer in the ZM or corrective ZM.
Appointments entered by the tax official, without a corrective ZM being issued by the tax office, do not replace the tax payer's pledge to issue a corrective ZM, but only lead to the correction of the data in the MIAS, so that they are up-to-date, complete and accurate.
The data from the CMs will be forwarded to the Member States concerned.
Only the national tax authority designated for cooperation with the other Member States in the area of VAT may transmit and receive this data.
This is the CLO (in the Czech Republic this function is performed by the Department of International Administrative Assistance in the field of VAT in the Ministry of Finance) and the "O _ MCTL" message is automatically received by the CLO from the other Member States.
It contains all incorrect USt-IdNr., which were specified in the transmitted ZM lines.
If the incorrect USt-IdNr. is used in some of the transmitted lines of the ZM or the corrected ZM, an entry is entered in the list of the wrong USt-IdNr.
The list contains a "message of doubts regarding USt-IdNr."
The financial officer checks the data and enters the result of the review into the system.
In the case of the purchase of goods from another Member State, the tax payer must state this in his VAT return and enter the value of the purchase in the relevant lines of the VAT return.
Selected cases of differences between the values of the acquisitions made by the Czech tax authority in its VAT return and the values for the delivery of goods indicated by the supplier from the other Member State in its ZM will be forwarded by the CLO to the competent FA for examination.
The staff there must investigate the deviations.
There can then be three different situations:
(a) The value indicated by the Czech purchaser in the relevant headings of his VAT return is lower than the value of the deliveries indicated by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, the financial officer checks the correctness of the information.
b) The difference is zero.
This situation may result either from a change in the information within the EC (the foreign supplier corrects his ZM) or from a change in the information in the VAT return (the Czech tax payer in the meantime makes a supplementary VAT return on his own initiative).
In this case, it is at the discretion of the tax official to check the accuracy of the information in the VAT return anyway.
(c) The value of the goods purchased from other Member States, as indicated by the Czech tax office in its VAT return, is higher than the value of the goods delivered by the suppliers of the other EC Member States.
Here, in turn, it is at the discretion of the financial official to verify the accuracy of the information.
After verifying the differences and clarifying the reasons for their occurrence, the financial officer enters the results of his review in ATIS.
These results will be forwarded to the CLO.
