Submission and processing of summary notifications in Germany
Entrepreneurs who make intra-Community deliveries from Germany to other EC Member States or participate in triangular transactions must surrender on a quarterly basis ZM in which intra-Community deliveries are listed by purchaser (§ 18a (1) UStG).
The ZM must be delivered no later than the 10th day of the month following the calendar quarter in question.
If a permanent extension is granted for the submission of the VAT advance notifications, this also applies to the ZM.
The ZM must be submitted to the CLO.
Since 1 January 2007, the electronic levy has been levied.
The competent FA can allow exemptions for individual tax payers in order to avoid unreasonable hardship.
If the tax payer finds that the ZM was faulty, it is leased to issue a corrective ZM within a month.
In the event of non-surrender of the ZM, the CLO initiates a forced procedure.
This includes the following steps: - first recollection - second recollection, combined with the threat of a penalty payment and - fixing the penalty payment.
Although the German tax code allows a penalty payment of up to €25,000 (§ 329 AO), the CLO sets fines of €125, 250 and 500 in three stages.
In addition, § 26a (1) No. 5 of the UStG stipulates that the tax payer acts unlawfully if he intentionally or recklessly does not surrender a ZM correctly, not completely or not in time or if he does not correct a ZM or does not correct it in time.
This infringement can be punishable by a fine of up to €5,000.
Data on intra-Community deliveries cannot be entered by the FÄ in the MIAS, because the processing of the ZM is exclusively the responsibility of the CLO.
The data of the ZM is stored only at the CLO.
The information from the summary notifications will only be available to the FÄ after they have been processed by the CLO.
The deadlines for processing ZM are laid down in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.
The data of the ZM must be stored within three months of the respective calendar quarter (in MIAS).
In the case of incorrect VAT ID numbers in the ZM of German tax authorities, the German CLO will receive a notification "O _ MCTL" from the other Member State.
The CLO then turns to the entrepreneur and asks for the right data.
If the CLO does not succeed in obtaining the correct information, the case will be referred to the relevant FA.
It is then up to them to request the right information.
In the course of its audit, the BRH found that most entrepreneurs corrected the VAT ID number at the request of the CLO.
However, it takes too much time to remember, as well as to threaten and impose up to three consecutive fines if a tax payer may be involved in a cross-border carousel fraud.
The cases, which were ultimately reported to the competent FÄ, were usually closed within one to two months.
The competent IAs refused to grant tax exemptions for notified intra-Community deliveries in 73% of these cases.
If the tax payer provided the correct VAT ID, the FA asked him to hand over a corrected ZM to the CLO because the FÄ cannot correct the MIAS data themselves.
The BRH found that neither the FÄ nor the CLO controlled the levy of the corrected ZM.
Since the CLO does not have access to the data of the VAT returns, there is no comparison of the information given in the VAT declarations or the VAT return with the corresponding information in the ZM before this data is forwarded to the CLO of the other Member States.
This comparison can only be made by the FÄ, which is usually done during the preparation of a special VAT audit.
Data received from other Member States will be processed by the CLO.
Incorrect VAT Items will be detected and reported to the Member States concerned.
The data will be used for the control of labour tax in the FÄ.
Once they are available in the system, it compares the CLO with the data of previous calendar quarters.
If they meet certain criteria (see 5.2), control notifications will be drawn up and sent to the competent FÄ.
This is done on an ongoing basis, whereas an auction of the acquisition data of all sales tax payers is later drawn up and forwarded to the FÄ.
The Risk Management System (RMS) for the investment procedure then compares these data with those for intra-Community acquisitions.
The system fully (only) checks those entrepreneurs who are not fully entitled to deduct the VAT.
Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax payers who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered for VAT in another Member State must surrender a ZM to the local FA within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
The FÄ process the ZM and forward the data to the CLO.
In the case of FÄ, the values of intra-Community deliveries reported by the tax authorities in the ZM are compared with the values of intra-Community deliveries indicated by the same tax authorities in their VAT returns.
The results of the settlement will be taken into account in the tax setting.
In Germany, tax payers who have made intra-Community deliveries are leased to surrender quarterly ZM within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter.
Since 1 January 2007, the tax authorities have to submit the ZM electronically to the CLO.
The data from the ZM are only available to the FÄ after their processing at the CLO.
In both the Czech Republic and Germany, the tax authorities in the ZM only indicate the deliveries of goods.
The provision of services is not indicated in the ZM. Unlike the Czech FÄ, the German FÄ cannot correct incorrect information in individual lines of the given ZM itself.
Due to this limited access to the German MIAS data, incorrect USt-ID was not corrected even if the tax payer informed the FA of the correct USt-ID number.
The German financial administration does not compare the information on intra-Community deliveries that German tax payers make in their VAT advance declarations with the information of the corresponding ZM.
Differences between the pre-registration data and the ZM are not regularly revealed before the German CLO transfers the MIAS data to other Member States.
On the basis of these findings of the BRH, it is obvious that a comparison would improve the reliability of the MIAS data transmitted.
The data transmitted by other Member States on deliveries of goods to Czech tax authorities will be compared in the Czech Republic with the data on purchases of goods indicated by the Czech tax authorities in their VAT returns.
The Czech CLO makes the comparison for each calendar quarter separately.
The most serious cases of derogations will be referred to the FÄ for examination.
Unlike the Czech financial administration, the German financial administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions.
Such general control will only be carried out in the case of tax payers who are not fully entitled to deduct VAT.
In addition, the German tax administration only controls the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions of other tax payers if the RMS produces an audit certificate or the tax payer has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves the FÄ of the clarification of the reasons for the differences that arise.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
In order to combat carousel fraud, updated information on intra-Community acquisitions must be available as early as possible.
The current system of the ZM, in particular MIAS, provides the financial authorities with information that may well be half a year old.
This time delay could be reduced to up to four months if the tax payers had to surrender monthly ZM.
The monthly levy would only slightly increase the bureaucratic burden, as most tax payers in the Czech Republic and Germany are already leased to submit monthly VAT returns or advance notifications and no more information is required for the ZM than for the VAT returns or advance notifications.
In order to avoid red tape, the levy of the ZM could be linked to the submission of the VAT declarations or advance notifications.
However, a default on the monthly levy of ZM would create more periodic discrepancies between the information on intra-Community deliveries and those on intra-Community acquisitions, and would increase the flow of data between the CLO.
In 2006, the Federal Government considered the general introduction of monthly ZM.
The implementation failed due to the concerns of the federal states.
They feared that a monthly transfer of MIAS data to the CLO of other Member States could lead to misunderstandings and confusion.
In order for the monthly levy of ZM to be effective, it is necessary to agree at European level on the single monthly levy, so that a monthly update of the MIAS data is possible.
