International exchange of information at level 3
International exchange of information in the Czech Republic
The international exchange of information allows tax officials to obtain information from other Member States on intra-Community transactions and on the tax payers who have carried them out.
Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 on mutual assistance in the field of VAT, repealing Directive (EEC) No 218 / 92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003"), distinguishes between two basic forms of exchange of information: the exchange of information on request and the spontaneous exchange of information (without prior request).
The international exchange of information on request is carried out by means of a request for information RFI using the standardized SCAC form.
Financial officials in the Czech Republic send their RFI or their replies to a received RFI through the Finance Directorate to the CLO, which is responsible for translating the information provided in the standardised SCAC form into the foreign language and for forwarding it to the other Member States.
In addition, the CLO receives requests for information (RFI) from other Member States and the replies to requests sent, and takes care of their translation into Czech and their distribution to the competent FÄ for processing.
Article 8 of Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 sets a maximum period of three months from receipt of the request for its processing.
All RFIs exchanged between the Czech Republic and Germany during the audited period were audited by the NKÚ.
Out of the total number of 94 RFIs received from Germany, 70 cases (i.e. 74.5%) were dealt with within the three-month period, while a further 23 cases (i.e. 24.5%) were exceeded.
In the remaining one case, no reply had been sent to Germany pending examination by the NKÚ. More detailed information on the deadlines within which requests made by Germany were answered by the Czech Republic can be found in Figure 2.
Out of the total number of 335 requests for information (RFIs) sent to Germany from the Czech Republic, 136 cases (i.e. 40.6%) received a reply within the three-month period; a further 179 (i.e. 53.4%) were processed after the expiry of this period and 19 cases had not yet received a reply from Germany (in the remaining one case it was not possible to determine when Germany answered the request for information on the basis of the information provided).
