The international exchange of information without prior request is either automatic, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
Financial officials from other Member States are often provided with information, without prior request, which is important for determining the VAT liability.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected at the CLO.
The exchange of information between the various Member States will take place electronically.
"Automatic exchange" under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 means the systematic transmission of previously established information to other Member States at regular, pre-determined intervals without prior request.
"Structured automatic exchange" means the systematic transmission of previously defined information to another Member State, without its prior request, as soon as the information in question is available.
The Czech Republic informs the other Member States about deliveries of new vehicles by means of automatic exchange of information.
This information is obtained by the financial officer from the form of notification of the delivery of a new vehicle in accordance with § 19 of Law No. 235 / 2004 and from the copy of the invoice issued.
When processing this form, the financial officer enters the required data into the relevant document and passes it directly on to the responsible staff of the Finance Directorate, where this data is collected and sent to the CLO for further processing, after which the data will be transmitted to the other Member States within the specified period, at the latest within two months of the end of the quarter in which it was obtained.
The Czech Republic also provides other Member States with information on mail order transactions that are tax-free in the country of origin, intra-Community transactions that appear inadmissible and potential "missing traders."
This information will be transmitted to the other Member States by means of a SCAC form in a spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information originates from the local FA.
The FÄ send the completed form SCAC 2004 by e-mail directly to the German CLO, which forwards the SCAC forms to the foreign CLO.
The FÄ are instructed to write their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the SCAC preprint used is one-language.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the Federal Republic of Germany were sent in order to ensure the taxation of labour in the other Member State or to demonstrate the tax exemption of intra-Community supplies from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German CLO receives a request for information from another Member State, it examines whether the value of the deliveries referred to in the request exceeds the minimum amount limit of €15,000.
If there is no reasonable justification for the request, the German CLO refuses to provide information on a turnover below the minimum amount limit.
In addition, the German CLO takes care of the translation of the freely formulated texts in the SCAC preprint [(B1-17) or (E)], if they are neither written in German nor in English.
In order to answer the request for information, the CLO directs it to the competent FA and refers to the three-month period.
No further deadlines have been set at the various levels of the German financial administration.
Although the German CLO has the technical means to monitor compliance with the deadline, it does not have the necessary personnel capacity to remind the FÄ to respond to the uncompleted requests for information.
The FÄ will receive the necessary information by writing to the tax office or carrying out an external audit.
The external auditors usually choose between two forms of audit: the special VAT audit, which covers all tax-related transactions within a period of several months, or the so-called VAT review, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
In this short and existential form of audit, an announcement to the tax payer is not necessary and it has proved its worth in investigating a single turnover.
In the case of automatic exchange of information, Germany will transmit to the other Member State the following information: - via VAT ID number allocated to companies established in other EC Member States - on the refund of VAT to entrepreneurs established in other EC Member States.
In addition, Germany has agreed to provide the following information to the other EC Member States in the context of the structured automatic exchange of information:
a. Delivery of new vehicles to traders without VAT No., b. Distance sales (mail order) to other EC Member States which are not subject to VAT in Germany, c. Significant deviations between the acquisitions reported by a tax payer and the MIAS data transmitted by other Member States, i.e. intra-Community deliveries of goods which have been incorrectly subject to taxation in Germany by the tax payer, e. potential "Missing Traders" who have made intra-Community transactions, irrespective of whether their use of the tax code is still valid or has already been deleted.
Comparison and evaluation
The sending of requests for information or spontaneous information takes place both in the Czech Republic and in Germany on the initiative of the local competent FÄ, which transmit the corresponding SCAC forms to the CLO.
Whereas the Czech CLO uses bilingual SCAC forms (Czech-English) and translates information given into English or German, the German FÄ follow the instruction to write requests for information or spontaneous information on a monolingual form only in German.
The German CLO does not produce translations of German texts.
When examining requests for information between the Czech Republic and Germany for the period 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005, the NKÚ found that 74.5% of requests for information received by the Czech financial administration were completed within the three-month period, while the requests for information addressed to Germany were only dealt with by the German financial administration in 40.6% of cases within that period.
Although the German CLO points the FÄ to the three-month period, it does not monitor its compliance.
Due to the lack of memories, there is a high proportion of temporary answers to requests for information.
For this reason, the BRH has recommended a continuous remembrance procedure to the German CLO.
The situation has now changed.
According to the information available to us, the German CLO is now reminding the tax offices of the answer to the outstanding requests for information.
VAT risk management
Risk management in the Czech Republic
In the Czech Republic, several organisational units at different levels of financial management are involved in risk management in the area of turnover tax.
Within the Czech Ministry of Finance, the following organisational units are responsible for risk management and the fight against VAT fraud:
The Sales Tax Methodology and Economic Management Department, or its Risk Management Unit, deals with the identification of potential risk areas for tax revenue and evaluates the trends in these risks in domestic and intra-Community trade.
At national level, this body coordinates the requirements for the "credibility of VAT returns" criterion and uses the MIAS data to detect possible tax evasion in the context of intra-Community deliveries and acquisitions.
Based on data on the Czech Republic's trade balance, it evaluates risky goods, prepares the concept of risk management in the area of VAT and cooperates in this area with the relevant EC institutions and the other Member States.
The Department for International Administrative Assistance in the field of VAT provides inter alia for the exchange of information, participates in the creation and planning of a relevant information database, evaluates the data available in the MIAS system from other Member States, carries out public relations work and is responsible for other forms of intergovernmental assistance within the meaning of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003.
