The Audit and Tax Investigation Methodology Department carries out, among other things, risk analyses in the framework of the methodological management of tax audits, sets priorities for the planning of the work of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of cases to be examined, draws up risk analyses to combat tax evasion and, in this context, collects information from the financial administration and other sources, and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Its tasks include the search for tax authorities and industries that are risky in terms of the frequency of tax evasion (e.g. Internet transactions, gold, the pharmaceutical industry), the search for unregistered tax payers (e.g. in the Internet services, employment agencies, electronic and print media, etc.), the investigation of chain fraud cases and the information to local tax authorities.
Special exam units have been set up in 12 selected FÄ.
They have a regional competence and, on the basis of appropriate authorization, carry out tax audits outside the local area of competence of the FÄ.
The need to set up the special audit units arose from the increase in new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly in the context of chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of tax investigators or focus on tax payers with certain activities, multinational companies and tax payers with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing risks in the area of VAT have been integrated into the ATIS system: - the task of "Credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk of tax returns issued; - the task of "selecting the taxable persons to be audited," selecting the taxable persons to be audited on the basis of certain criteria; - the task of "MIAS," which allows financial officials access to the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The "MIAS" task allows, among other things: - verification of the validity of the VAT ID number of tax payers from other Member States; - confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech tax payer as indicated in the ZM by all suppliers of the tax payer in question from other Member States; - compilation of a list of tax payers who have not surrendered a ZM; - formal control of the information provided by tax payers in the Czech Republic in their Member States before such information is transmitted to other Member States; - compilation of a list of tax payers whose VAT declarations do not correspond to the VAT declarations in the other Member States; - compilation of a list of tax payers whose VAT declarations do not correspond to the VAT declarations in the CM of all other Member States.
As part of their role in the fight against tax evasion, financial officials have access to data from public authorities such as commercial registers, land registers, motor vehicle registers, business registers, etc.
More detailed information can be found in Section 4.4.1 of Submission and Processing of Summary Notifications in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
Due to their federal structure, both the federal authorities (in particular the CLO) and the financial administrations of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and introduction of an RMS in the Federal Republic of Germany.
It is true that there are joint development working groups, but neither the CLO nor the financial administrations of the federal states have a complete set of data.
At the level of the CLO, Unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as "KUSS" - Coordination Centre for Special Value Added Tax Audit and Tax Investigation Measures) collects the audit findings on fraud in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER has been set up at KUSS, where the tax offices can enter and query the names of discovered Missing Traders or VAT fraudsters.
The KUSS coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the KUSS is brought into the development of the RMS through its cooperation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organisational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of VAT numbers of other Member States, which appear in the ZM of German tax authorities, will be carried out at the CLO.
This formal review takes place prior to the transmission of the ZM to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and thus its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The validity of the VAT ID number referred to in the ZM is verified on the basis of the O _ MCTL identifiers transmitted by the other Member States (for the procedure for correcting invalid VAT ID number, see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the RMS of the CLO is based on the MIAS data transmitted by the other Member States and generates various types of notifications for the discovery of suspected missing traders, using certain characteristics that usually occur in carousel transactions.
The FÄ of the federal states are instructed to process these notifications and must forward the result of their investigations to the CLO in certain cases.
The BRH's audit confirmed that all available features must be taken into account in order to be sufficiently likely to conclude a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH has recommended to the BMF to work with combinations of different clues in the preparation of the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other indications, such as the payment behaviour of the tax payer, the industry or the company's shareholdings.
A second level of risk management exists with the financial administrations of the federal states and focuses on the processing of VAT advance notifications and annual declarations.
For example, the system compiles a list of those tax payers who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their VAT declaration or annual declaration.
This list will be sent to the CLO for the purpose of monitoring the complete surrender of the ZM.
In addition, in this type of risk management, the acquisitions indicated by the tax payer in his annual VAT return are compared with the data in the MIAS.
The financial administrations of the federal states avoid comparing the quarterly data, as these would result in too many inconsistencies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; e.g.:
- Supplier and purchaser assume different dates for the execution of intra-Community transactions;
- different accounting records and tax declaration of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the data from the VAT returns with the MIAS data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms, which are based on information in the VAT returns and certain other indications (e.g. company wording, age of the owner / shareholder, number of employees and method of payment of the tax payer).
Bavaria has introduced a rule-based risk management system that allows a team of specialists in the fight against tax fraud (hereinafter referred to as "risk managers") to program its own rules in such a way that suspected tax fraudsters are identified.
This system is used in the processing of VAT notifications by the FÄ.
As a result, the competent FA receives the information from the RMS before the sales tax is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, risk managers must adapt the rules according to the feedback from the FÄ.
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of detected evasion cases.
On the basis of this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system draws up a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent FÄ will decide on the examination of the tax plans in question.
After the audit, the auditors will have to report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the audits it proposes.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rule-based fuzzy system.
Based on many data from processed VAT returns and some other evidence, this neuro-fuzzy system (also known as the datamining system) calculates how likely it is that a tax payer is involved in tax fraud.
It then compiles a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, the FÄ select the relevant tax breakers for examination and report the audit results to the data center concerned.
The introduction of these three RMS is under way in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems seems to be a good idea.
Whether the hoped-for effects will materialize during actual use remains to be seen.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in the present report to deal with the specific criteria of RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
As well as the different approaches in the three German federal states mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud - in particular carousel fraud - has proved to be a European problem, not a national one.
The persons involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one Member State, but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State; if this does not happen, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is established.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud may be affected.
That is why there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
Selected results from the audit of individual sales In the context of the parallel audits, NKÚ and BRH examined the quality and usability of information on selected deliveries and / or deliveries.
acquisitions which were the subject of the international exchange of information between the financial administrations of the Czech Republic and Germany.
In addition, the two jurisdictions jointly examined the handling of several deliveries about which there were doubts about the implementation, or which the tax authorities of both states explained differently in the tax returns or ZM.
At the request of the BRH, the NKÚ examined a total of eight business incidents between eight Czech and eight German tax payers.
In addition, in 43 cases, on the basis of communications from the BRH, the NKÚ examined the values of intra-Community transactions with Germany, which Czech tax authorities had indicated in their tax returns and ZM.
At the request of the NKÚ, the BRH reviewed a total of 23 deliveries between 23 German and 21 Czech tax payers.
The relevant information was exchanged exclusively on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the CLO.
Examination of the selected cases showed, among other things, that the different registration procedures in the EC Member States lead to the problems identified in Chapter 4.1:
1.
According to the MIAS data, a Czech tax payer acquired goods worth €60,500 from a German tax payer in the third quarter of 2004.
When the Czech tax payer declared a purchase of only €29,869, the Czech tax administration sent a request for information to Germany for verification of the value of the goods delivered.
In response to the Czech request for information, the German side stated that the German tax payer in question had delivered goods worth €27,381 to its Czech business partner in the second quarter of 2004, goods worth €31,997 in the third quarter and goods worth €10,276 in the fourth quarter.
However, the German CLO had accepted a further application from the German tax authority and brought forward the validity of the USt-IdNr. retroactively as of May 1, 2004.
The German tax payer corrected the ZM.
On the basis of this information, it was a (intra-Community) purchase of goods by the Czech tax authorities.
In a request to the competent tax office in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that in 2004 the Czech tax payer had issued supplementary VAT returns for the individual (lower) tax periods during which it declared a higher value of purchases from other Member States and at the same time requested the deduction of VAT from acquisitions from other Member States.
On the basis of these additional VAT returns, the competent representative of the Czech Tax Office could not clearly determine whether the declared acquisitions also included the value of the deliveries of the above-mentioned German supplier.
In response to a request for information from the NKÚ, the BRH found that the German supplier had been registered as a sales tax issuer in September 2003.
At the time of registration, he had not applied for the allocation of a VAT ID number, but only a tax number valid exclusively for Germany.
Although it is usually not possible in Germany to retroactively allocate a VAT ID number to a tax payer, in 2006 the responsible person of the German financial administration did so retroactively as of 1 May 2004.
The German CLO retroactively allocates a USt-ID number if the German entrepreneur has not caused the delayed allocation; for example, if the CLO caused the delay after the tax payer applied for a USt-ID number.
In this case, the CLO grants the USt-IdNr. retroactively, because according to § 6 of the UStG the entrepreneur does not need a valid USt-IdNr. for an intra-Community delivery.
Conversely, a German purchaser does not need the (valid) VAT ID of its supplier in order to declare the intra-Community acquisition.
In view of these procedural differences between the Member States, the German CLO granted the VAT ID number retroactively in this particular case.
2.
In the context of the international exchange of information, the Czech finance official asked for a review of the German entrepreneur's turnover tax registration.
According to the MIAS data, the date of registration is 5 March 2005, while a registration certificate issued by the local competent German FA indicates 1 October 2004.
In their reply, the German authorities announced that the German tax payer had been registered on 1 October 2004, but for organisational reasons had only been allocated a VAT ID number in Germany on 16 February 2005.
Through a request from the local Czech finance official, the NKÚ learned that the financial officer had carried out a VAT audit at the Czech tax office for the tax periods from the third quarter of 2004 to the second quarter of 2005.
During this investigation, the tax office found that the Czech tax payer had declared in his VAT return services worth CZK 9,897, which he had provided to the German tax payer before his sales tax registration (i.e. before 1 October 2004).
The (Czech) tax office set a tax debt of CZK 1,880 against the Czech tax payer for the third quarter of 2004.
In response to the NKÚ's request, the BRH found that the German tax payer had only been allocated the VAT ID number when he registered his company, which was founded in 2004, with the FA on 16 February 2005.
In addition, the FA registered it retroactively from 1 October 200415 for sales tax purposes in order to be able to monitor the delivery of the VAT return for 2004.
In this VAT return, the tax payer stated intra-Community acquisitions from the Czech Republic worth 160 €(approx. 5,000 CZK).
3. In its sales tax return for September 2004 as well as in its ZM for the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax payer stated correct deliveries of goods worth CZK 114,615 to a German tax payer.
When verifying the registration of the German tax payer in the MIAS system, the Czech financial official found that this registration was only valid from 11 November 2004 and thus after the deliveries of goods to Germany.
The Czech tax payer issued a supplementary VAT return in which he declared sales from domestic deliveries worth CZK 114,615 and sales tax of CZK 21,777, which he paid.
In a request to the local FA in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax payer subsequently submitted an application for the resumption of the tax procedure with regard to the supplementary VAT return, as proof that the German tax payer had been registered since 1 January 2000.
Accordingly, the Czech finance official checked the validity of the registration of the German tax payer in the context of the international exchange of information.
The German information showed that the German tax payer had only been assigned a VAT ID number on 11 November 2004, i.e. after the date of delivery of the goods.
As a result, the Czech finance official rejected the request to resume the tax procedure.
The BRH found that in this case no intra-Community purchase of goods had taken place because the German tax payer had only received a VAT ID number on 11 November 2004.
However, the German recipient declared both the acquisition as an intra-Community acquisition and the turnover tax on this and also demanded the reimbursement of the same amount of advance taxes.
Because this did not lead to a change in the amount of the tax debt of the German tax payer, the German financial official did not correct the information in the VAT return.
The BRH also found that the company of the German tax payer named in the request for information was changed during the processing of the answer in Germany, leading to confusion between two German tax payers.
This change in the name of the German tax payer also confused the Czech financial official.
4.
As part of the international exchange of information, the German financial official reviewed the purchase of goods in the first quarter of 2005 by a Czech tax payer from a German tax payer worth €22,686.
In a request to the local tax official in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that, as part of an external audit, the Czech tax official had checked with the Czech tax payer whether the intra-Community delivery had actually taken place and whether the Czech tax payer had recorded and paid the invoice for the delivery of the goods.
The Czech tax payer did not explain the intra-Community acquisition in his VAT return, because the German supplier did not specify his VAT ID number in the invoice but only his tax number intended for business within Germany.
According to the MIAS data, the German tax payer will not be registered for VAT in connection with intra-Community transactions until 21 April 2005, i.e. after delivery to the Czech tax payers.
The Czech financial official also requested that the German financial administration send a copy of the registration certificate of the German tax payer so that he could initiate an appropriate tax procedure if necessary.
The Czech FA considered this transaction to be the purchase of goods from a non-entrepreneurial (private) person in Germany and therefore did not set a VAT on the purchase of the goods from Germany.
The BRH found that under German law, a tax payer supplying goods to other Member States does not have to have a VAT ID number for intra-Community deliveries in order to be able to benefit from the VAT exemption for such a supply.
The supplier must only have the purchaser's VAT number in the other Member State and be able to prove the transport of the goods concerned to the other Member State.
In this case, under German tax law, the turnover is a (tax-exempt) intra-Community supply, which should be subject to occupational taxation in the Czech Republic.
In any case, it is important that the Czech finance official took note of this business incident, because the supply of a machine of this value was not part of the core business of the German supplier.
As described in Section 4.6.2, the German CLO rejects requests for information on intra-Community transactions if they are below the minimum amount limit of €15,000:5.
According to MIAS data, a Czech tax payer acquired goods worth €12,561 from a German tax payer in the third quarter of 2004.
The Czech financial official carried out an audit for this tax period.
In the context of the intergovernmental assistance, the Czech financial administration requested the examination of this supply of goods by means of a SAC-form.
The Czech tax payer said he had not received the goods, had never been in business with the German company and that the purchase of the goods in question had not been recorded with him.
