In the context of the international exchange of information, the German financial administration requested a review of the delivery of goods and the provision of services in the third quarter of 2005 by means of a SCAC form.
According to the request for information, during the period in question, the Czech tax payer had delivered goods worth a total of €396,126 to the German tax payer and provided services worth €11,885.
The NKÚ found that the Czech financial administration had carried out an audit of the Czech tax payer in order to investigate this delivery.
In response to the request for information, the Czech financial administration announced that the Czech tax payer had supplied and assembled a production plant to the German one.
The Czech tax authority supplied the individual parts of the production plant before the accession of the Czech Republic to the EC and the production plant was assembled on the basis of the order after 1 May 2004.
The German tax payer did not take off the assembled production plant and claimed defects.
In the third quarter of 2005, the Czech tax payer charged the German production plant for €107,100 and €11,885 for services.
The German tax payer received the bills, but did not recognise them and did not pay them.
By asking the local tax official in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that all invoices had been duly recorded in the books of the Czech tax office.
The sales tax returns for the third quarter of 2005 contained only the amounts documented by the Czech tax authorities and related to invoices invoiced after the first of May 2004.
The BRH found that, on the basis of the reply from the Czech financial administration, the local FA concluded that these transactions were a uniform (goods) delivery of the Czech tax payer to the German one, including the assembly carried out.
In this particular case, the place of fulfilment of this so-called factory delivery is the place where the production plant is assembled.
The German service recipient of the factory delivery owes the sales tax in accordance with the German sales tax law.
At the same time, the recipient can claim a deduction of the same amount.
Since the VAT liability of the German tax payer remained unchanged, the German FA did not cause a correction of the VAT return.
