He received the machine at the headquarters of the branch of the German tax payer in the Czech Republic.
Since this delivery (from C to A) took place only within the Czech Republic, there was no intra-Community delivery of goods.
In a request to the local tax official responsible for the tax payer B, the NKÚ found that, according to MIAS data, the German tax payer C had delivered goods (another machine) worth €88,027 to the Czech tax payer in the third quarter of 2004.
The tax payer B said it had not received this goods, so the local Czech finance official sent a request for information to Germany.
The answer was that the machine had been delivered.
In the course of further investigations at the tax payer B, the financial official found that the machine, worth €88,027, had not been recorded at the tax payer B and that it could be the same type of machine as the branch of the German tax payer C had delivered to the Czech tax payer A in February 2005.
The NKÚ also found that the Czech financial official responsible for the tax break A had carried out an audit on it.
The finance official had the invoice of the German tax payer C of 7 February 2005, in which the tax payer A is indicated as the recipient of the machine.
The Czech financial official noted that the tax payer A had not recorded this bill.
