By asking the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ found that after receiving the reply from Germany, he had contacted the accountant of the Czech tax office and remained with her in such a way that, after checking the invoices, she wanted to talk to the company owner about the submission of a supplementary VAT return for the third quarter of 2004.
So far, no supplementary VAT return has been issued.
The Czech financial official informed the NKÚ that he would proceed in such a way that the deadlines for a retroactive VAT fixing for the tax period in question would be respected.
17.
In the fourth quarter of 2004, the German tax payer delivered goods worth €11,600 to the German tax payer.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information, the German financial official asked for a review of whether the aforementioned Czech tax payers actually existed, as the alleged capital owner of the German tax payer had set up a number of bogus rents in Germany.
In the course of the FA's review of the transaction, the Czech tax payer confirmed the purchase of the goods.
According to the Czech tax office, however, the goods were not delivered from Germany to the Czech Republic, but resold in Germany in 2005.
The Czech tax payer submitted evidence of the sale in January 2005.
The Czech tax payer was not registered as a sales tax payer in Germany and had not taxed the sale of the goods in question in the Czech Republic or in Germany.
All of these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany, and the Czech finance official forwarded this information to the German financial administration in his response to the request for information.
By asking the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ found that, on the basis of a tax audit, the Czech tax payer had issued a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004, in which he declared, among other things, the value of the goods he had acquired from a German tax payer and at the same time asserted the right to deduct VAT for the purchase from other Member States.
In his Czech VAT return, he did not report any sales tax on the sale of goods in Germany.
On the basis of a supplementary VAT return, which had been issued after the external audit, the Czech financial official fixed the VAT debt unchanged.
According to Czech legislation, in this case there was no purchase of goods from other Member States, as the goods were not shipped or transported to the Czech Republic by another Member State.
As a result, the Czech financial official drew the wrong conclusion in the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which showed that the goods had not left Germany, the German tax official corrected the tax return of the German tax payer and demanded the payment of sales tax worth €1,600.
In addition, the competent FA sent a control notice to the FA responsible for the actual recipient of the goods in order to ensure that the resale of these goods is duly taxed.
