18.
The Czech finance official received a request for information from the German financial administration on the question of whether the Czech tax payer had purchased a car worth €47,400 from the German tax payer in February 2005.
The request for information was accompanied by an imprint of the VAT registration certificate of the Czech tax payer as an annex.
As a further installation, a photocopy of the passport of the person who was supposed to have transferred the vehicle was attached.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech finance official found that the passport had been stolen, that the person named in it had not imported a vehicle into the Czech Republic and said she had no contacts with a German tax payer.
The VAT registration certificate, the imprint of which had been sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech financial administration.
With this information, the Czech finance official responded to the request for information and at the same time stated that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
By asking the local Czech finance official, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax payer does not have his registered office at the address indicated in the commercial register and that the managing director of the company is not reachable.
Following a tax complaint procedure for the February 2005 tax period, the Czech tax official set the tax debt of the Czech tax payer at zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech finance official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had acquired it on the basis of an internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local German financial official had rejected the German tax payer's claim to exempt this delivery from sales tax on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the purchased goods stated in the VAT return and the reported values from other Member States.
A Czech tax payer was supposed to have delivered goods worth €89,424 to a German tax payer in the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005.
Since the acquisition declared by the German tax office did not correspond to the MIAS data, the German financial official asked for the verification of the deliveries and their payment as part of the intergovernmental exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech finance official stated that the only managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was presumably a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech tax payer issued a VAT return and a ZM, which had been signed by an unauthorised person, namely that shareholder of the company, after the deletion of the managing director in the commercial register.
The accountant of the Czech tax payer informed the financial official that the capital owner had deposited the payment received in euros for the goods invoiced into the company's account.
Cash receipts were not issued.
By request to the local competent Czech FA, the NKÚ found that the financial official had recognised the Czech tax official's right to VAT exemption for deliveries of goods to other Member States amounting to CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German financial official did not correct the German acquirer's VAT return, as in the meantime a German court had confirmed the insolvency of the German tax payer.
Since the previous external audit showed no evidence of tax fraud, there was no prospect of actually being able to levy a fixed VAT debt.
20. According to the MIAS data, a German tax payer acquired goods from the Czech Republic worth €4,251,196 in 2005, after which he had purchased goods worth €43,274 in the previous year.
The German tax payer did not declare the intra-Community acquisitions in its 2004 VAT return or in the for 2005.
In addition, he did not declare any starting sales in terms of value.
Due to these inconsistencies, the German FA submitted a request for information concerning the 4th quarter of 2005 and the 1st quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community deliveries of goods with a total value of CZK 167,246,083.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side asked to check whether the delivery notified by the Czech tax authorities had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech Finance Administration stated that the German request could not be complied with because the Czech company did not have a managing director (or other legal representative).
The documents handed over to the NKÚ by the competent financial officer show that, together with the managing director of the Czech tax office, a protocol on the commencement of the VAT audit for the 4th quarter of 2004 and the period January to December 2005 had been drawn up on 30 March 2006.
At the same time, the tax officer was asked by the tax official to provide all accounting and tax documents for that period, but failed to do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the sole managing director expired on 16 May 2005 without a new managing director being appointed.
The Czech tax payer has not issued any sales tax returns since April 2006.
In the context of the parallel investigation, NKÚ, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community deliveries between the Czech Republic and Germany which were not the subject of a prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two auditors exchanged information on the audited cases through the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the competent FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to do tax-related business in Germany.
On the basis of this information, the company was registered in June 2005, but did not receive a German USt-IdNr.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the production and delivery of wind turbines to Austria on behalf, at the risk and on behalf of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient production capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the contract to a German tax payer (UDE) based in Germany.
The following figure shows the contractual relations and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria for assembly on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account.
Due to the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
Because the forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out on its own behalf, at its own risk and for its own account, the place of delivery of the German subcontractor (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as taxable in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the supply of the German sub-contractor (UDE), since the EC Member State for which the supply was intended is different from the home country of the Czech company 19.
Accordingly, the delivery is duly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
The delivery of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
The delivery of the remaining wind turbines manufactured in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided both intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community deliveries either in its German tax returns or in its ZM issued to the German CLO.
As a result, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community supplies uniformly as intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic.
The NKÚ found that (UCR) did not notify intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, cooperation between at least four financial administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be necessary, although there is no evidence of tax fraud or tax evasion in this case.
In addition, the NKÚ and the BRH examined case formulations in order to show the size of the differences between the information in the VAT returns and the MIAS data caused by the different legislation of 2004.
The cases examined also show that it will take some time for the tax payers and the FÄ to apply the new legislation:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech tax payer reported a total value of CZK 792,977,452 to a German tax payer.
During the same period, another Czech tax payer in its ZM reported intra-Community deliveries to another German tax payer with a total value of CZK 18,157,265.
The information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that both were electricity supplies.
Both Czech tax authorities took into account the above-mentioned deliveries in their ZM in accordance with Czech Law No 235 / 2004, which was in force in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of the NKÚ found that in 2004 there were different legal provisions on the supply or acquisition of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany.
Whereas in the Czech Republic the tax authorities declared the deliveries of electrical energy as intra-Community deliveries in accordance with the provisions of Law No. 235 / 2004 in force in 2004, according to the German legal provisions in force in 2004, it was not an intra-Community purchase of goods, but taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in legislation in the Czech Republic were eliminated by the adoption of Law No 635 / 2004, which amended some tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. During the examination of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech tax payer in his ZM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 declared intra-Community deliveries to a German tax payer with a total value of CZK 240,411,163 and another Czech tax payer in his ZM for the same period declared intra-Community deliveries to another German tax payer with a value of CZK 263,470,776.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that in both cases they were supplies of electrical energy.
In accordance with the wording of Law No 235 / 2004, which will apply from 1 January 2005 onwards, the place of performance in the case of the supply of electrical energy shall be the place where the purchaser has his legal domicile, place of business or place of business for which such delivery takes place.
Therefore, the Czech tax authorities should not have indicated the electricity deliveries in their ZM for 2005.
The fact that both tax authorities treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies led to a difference of CZK 503,881,939 in MIAS.
Final remark
The cooperation has achieved the objectives of the BRH and the NKÚ.
Both auditors gained in-depth knowledge of the systems of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legal regulations governing the administration of VAT.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions were revealed.
For some of them, further observation is worthwhile.
On the basis of the audit results, both auditors drew up recommendations on the management of the turnover tax.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a verification exercise should be part of further monitoring.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of the two auditors will form the basis for the successful conduct of future audits in the area of VAT management.
